ew Party]] at-large party list.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Yu |first1=Matt |last2=Chen |first2=Christie |title=CEC to review legality of ex-president's legislative bid |url=http://focustaiwan.tw/news/aipl/201911210009.aspx |accessdate=21 November 2019 |agency=Central News Agency |date=21 November 2019}}</ref>  The New Party did not meet the 5% vote threshold and therefore none of its party list legislators were elected.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.ltn.com.tw/news/politics/breakingnews/3037474|title=\u90b1\u6bc5\u7acb\u59d4\u5922\u788e\uff01\u653f\u9ee8\u7968\u53ea\u62ff1\uff05 \u65b0\u9ee8\u4e0d\u5206\u5340\u5168\u69d3|date=January 11, 2020|trans-title=Chiu Yi's electoral dreams dashed!  New Party receives only 1% of the votes, no party list legislators elected|language=Chinese|access-date=April 28, 2020|work=[[Liberty Times]]}}</ref>\n\n== Cross-strait relations ==\n\nIn March of 2019, during a cross-strait forum in [[Fujian]], he stated that pro-independence figures could be beheaded during an annexation of Taiwan by China.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://topics.amcham.com.tw/2019/12/taiwan-life-in-brief-december/|title=Taiwan Life in Brief \u2013 December 2019|first=Jeremy|last=Oliver|work=[[American Chamber of Commerce in Taipei]], Taiwan Business TOPICS|date=December 9, 2019|access-date=April 28, 2020}}</ref> In December 2019, he was criticized for appearing on Chinese state media discussing details of Taiwan's defense systems.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2019/12/19/2003727799|title=Chiu Yi called \u2018traitor\u2019 for military strategy claims|date=December 19, 2019|access-date=April 28, 2020|work=[[Taipei Times]]|last=1=Chung|first1=Li-hua|last2=Hetherington|first2=William}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\n\nChiu was indicted in April 2004 for attempting to break into the Kaohsiung District Court building after the announcement of [[Chen Shui-bian]]'s presidential election victory, for which he was sentenced to serve a year in prison.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2006/08/19/2003323805|title=Chiu Yi sentenced for southern ram raid|work=[[Taipei Times]]|date=August 19, 2006|access-date=April 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2006, he filed a special funds abuse lawsuit against then-president [[Chen Shui-bian]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2006/07/21/2003319701|title=KMT's Chiu Yi files suit against Chen Shui-bian|work=[[Taipei Times]]|last=Shih|first=Hsiu-chuan|date=July 21, 2006|access-date=April 28, 2020}}</ref>.  In November 2019, he filed a defamation lawsuit against Taipei mayor [[Ko Wen-je]] for a comment that his nomination for the Kuomintang and New Party legislator-at-large list in the [[2020 Taiwanese legislative election]] could indicate that China's [[Taiwan Affairs Office]] has \"control\" over the two parties.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2019/11/26/2003726509|title=Ko says comments \u2018honest\u2019 after Chiu Yi files a lawsuit|access-date=April 28, 2020|date=November 26, 2019|last=Lee|first=I-chia|work=[[Taipei Times]]}}</ref>.\n\nIn January 2008, he was found guilty of slander for accusing DPP chairman [[Yu Shyi-kun]] of illegal lobbying.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2008/01/20/2003398016|title=Chiu Yi found guilty of slander|first=Rich|last=Chang|work=[[Taipei Times]]|date=January 20, 2008|access-date=April 28, 2020}}</ref>  In 2015 he was sued twice by the DPP for defamation over statements he made regarding presidential candidate [[Tsai Ing-wen]]'s real-estate dealings.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2015/12/15/2003634825|title=DPP sues KMT trio over Tsai claims|work=[[Taipei Times]]|date=December 15, 2015|access-date=April 28, 2020|last=Loa|first=Iok-sin}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2015/12/24/2003635542|title=DPP files second lawsuit against Alex Tsai, Chiu Yi|work=[[Taipei Times]]|date=December 24, 2015|last=Loa|first=Iok-sin|access-date=April 28, 2020}}</ref>  Former KMT president [[Ma Ying-jeou]] also considered a lawsuit against Chiu in 2020 for alleging that Ma was responsible for his removal from the KMT legislator-at-large party list in the [[2020 Taiwanese legislative election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.taipeitimes.com/News/front/archives/2019/11/22/2003726277|title=Ma Ying-jeou mulls defamation suit against Chiu|first=Ann|last=Maxon|date=November 22, 2019|access-date=April 28, 2020|work=[[Taipei Times]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{commons category|Chiu Yi}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chiu, Yi}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Kuomintang Members of the Legislative Yuan in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:National Taiwan University alumni]]\n[[Category:Kaohsiung Members of the Legislative Yuan]]\n[[Category:People First Party Members of the Legislative Yuan]]\n[[Category:Members of the 5th Legislative Yuan]]\n[[Category:Members of the 6th Legislative Yuan]]\n[[Category:Members of the 7th Legislative Yuan]]\n[[Category:Party List Members of the Legislative Yuan]]\n[[Category:New Party (Republic of China) politicians]]\n\n\n{{Taiwan-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "Alter: trans-title, title. | You canuse this toolyourself.Report bugs here. | via #UCB_Gadget", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chiu_Yi"}
